Tariff Submitter: Northwest Ohio IA, LLC FERC Tariff Program: FERC Electric Tariff - MBR Tariff Title: Tariffs and Agreements Tariff Record Proposed Effective Date: 2/4/2023 Tariff Record Description: Shared Facilities Agrmt. Tariff Record Title: Amended & Restated SFA with NW Ohio Wind & NW Ohio Solar Option Code: A
AMENDED AND RESTATED SHARED FACILITIES AGREEMENT This AMENDED AND RESTATED SHARED FACILITIES AGREEMENT (this “Agreement”) is entered into as of [_______], 2022 (the “Effective Date”), by and among Northwest Ohio Wind, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (“Northwest Ohio Wind”), Northwest Ohio Solar, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (“Northwest Ohio Solar”; Northwest Ohio Wind and Northwest Ohio Solar each individually a “Co-User” and collectively “Co-Users”), and Northwest Ohio IA, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company, as interconnection company and manager (“Interconnection Company”). Northwest Ohio Wind, Northwest Ohio Solar, and Interconnection Company may be referred to herein individually as a “Party” and collectively as the “Parties.” RECITALS WHEREAS, Northwest Ohio Wind owns and operates a wind powered electricity generating project with a total nameplate capacity of approximately 105 MW located in Paulding County, Ohio (the “Northwest Ohio Wind Project”); WHEREAS, Northwest Ohio Solar separately owns and operates a solar powered electricity generating project with a total nameplate capacity of approximately 3.52 MW and a DC-coupled lithium-ion battery with 3.44 MWh nameplate capacity in Paulding County, Ohio (the “Northwest Ohio Solar Project” and, together with the Northwest Ohio Wind Project, the “Projects”); WHEREAS, Northwest Ohio Wind owns, leases and/or operates certain personal property, real property, fixtures, easements, equipment and facilities that are necessary for the operation, interconnection, and maintenance of the Projects, as set forth in Exhibit A attached hereto (the “Shared Facilities”); WHEREAS, Northwest Ohio Wind and Northwest Ohio Solar are the sole members of Interconnection Company; WHEREAS Northwest Ohio Solar desires to use, and Northwest Ohio Wind desires to grant Northwest Ohio Solar the right to use, the Shared Facilities on the terms and conditions set forth herein; WHEREAS, Northwest Ohio Wind and Northwest Ohio Solar are parties to that certain Amended and Restated Solar Generation and Storage Lease Agreement, dated as of the date hereof (as amended, amended and restated or otherwise modified from time to time, the “Lease”); WHEREAS, Northwest Ohio Wind is a party to a Renewable Energy Purchase Agreement, dated as of July 20, 2017 (as amended, amended and restated or otherwise modified as of the date hereof and from time to time, the “REPA”); WHEREAS, Northwest Ohio Wind is a party to that certain Interconnection Service Agreement (PJM Queue Position #AF2-103), dated as of January 28, 2021, among PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. (“PJM”), Northwest Ohio Wind and AEP Ohio Transmission Company, Inc. (“AEP”) (as amended, amended and restated or otherwise modified from time to time, the “ISA”); WHEREAS, Northwest Ohio Wind intends to assign the ISA to the Interconnection Company pursuant to an assignment and assumption agreement in a form acceptable to the Parties (the “ISA Assignment”) and evidenced by the Consent to Assignment Agreement, by and among PJM Interconnection, L.L.C., Northwest Ohio Wind, LLC, Northwest Ohio IA, LLC, and AEP Ohio Transmission Company, Inc., and executed by Northwest Ohio Wind, LLC, and Northwest Ohio IA, LLC, on October 27, 2022 (the “ISA Consent to Assignment”); WHEREAS, for purposes of this Agreement, the Projects and the Shared Facilities shall collectively constitute the “Customer Facility” and the “Customer Interconnection Facilities” as those terms are defined in the ISA, and are collectively referred to herein as the “Project Facility”; WHEREAS, the Co-Users desire to provide the Interconnection Company with access to and control of the Project Facility in order for the Interconnection Company to fulfill its obligations on behalf of the Co-Users under the ISA; WHEREAS, the Parties previously entered into that certain Shared Facilities Agreement, dated as of June 24, 2022 (the “Prior Agreement”); and WHEREAS, the Parties wish to amend and restate the Prior Agreement as set forth herein. NOW THEREFORE, in consideration of the premises and of the mutual covenants and agreements contained herein, and for other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and sufficiency of which is hereby acknowledged, the Parties hereby agree as follows: AGREEMENT 1. TERM; EARLY TERMINATION; CONDITIONS PRECEDENT 1.1 Term: This Agreement shall become effective upon the satisfaction of the Conditions Precedent set forth in Section 1.2 below, and shall continue in effect until terminated (a) by mutual agreement of the Parties or (b) pursuant to Section 1.3 of this Agreement; provided, however, that, without limiting the obligations of Northwest Ohio Solar hereunder, the Parties acknowledge and agree that the Interconnection Company shall have no obligations with respect to the Project Facility and that Northwest Ohio Wind shall act as the “Interconnection Customer” under the ISA until the occurrence of the “Assignment Date” (as such term is defined in, and established pursuant to Section 8.0 of, the ISA Consent to Assignment). 1.2 Condition Precedent: Notwithstanding anything herein to the contrary, all of Parties’ obligations hereunder are conditioned on (i) Interconnection Company’s receipt of an order from the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (“FERC”) that accepts or approves this Agreement, which order shall be final and non-appealable and satisfactory to Northwest Ohio Wind, (ii) Interconnection Company obtains the necessary authorizations from FERC and PJM to sell energy and/or capacity at wholesale, and the ISA has been assigned from Northwest Ohio Wind to Interconnection Company and the “Assignment Date” (as such term is defined in, and established pursuant to Section 8.0 of, the ISA Consent to Assignment) has occurred, and (iii) Northwest Ohio Solar obtains the necessary authorizations, if required, from FERC and PJM to allow energy and/or capacity from its Project to be sold at wholesale. 1.3 Early Termination: Unless earlier terminated pursuant to Section 8.2 hereof, this Agreement shall automatically terminate, subject to obtaining any necessary ISA amendments and prior authorizations and approvals required by applicable law with respect to such termination, including from FERC, without further action by either Party and without further liability of one Party to the other attributable to such early termination, upon the date that either Northwest Ohio Wind or Northwest Ohio Solar, or their respective successors and assigns, has permanently ceased operation of its generating facility for the production of electric energy. 1.4 Decommissioning Obligations: If this Agreement terminates or expires, Northwest Ohio Solar shall be responsible for all actions taken and all costs incurred by Northwest Ohio Wind or Interconnection Company, as a result of such termination, including costs and expenses associated with (a) the disconnection, decommissioning and removal from the Shared Facilities of any equipment or other property that is owned by or installed for the benefit of, the Northwest Ohio Solar Project; and (b) securing any regulatory approvals or authorizations that may be required from the FERC, PJM, or any Governmental Authority, in connection with the termination or expiration of this Agreement. As used herein, “Governmental Authority” shall mean any foreign, domestic, federal, territorial, state or local governmental authority, court, commission, board, bureau, agency or instrumentality, or any regulatory, administrative or other department, agency, or any political or other subdivision, department or branch of any of the foregoing, any taxing authority and any electric reliability organization, regional transmission organization or independent system operator, including, without limitation, FERC, the North American Electric Reliability Corporation (and Reliability First Corporation) (“NERC”), PJM or, in each case, any successor thereto. 2. GRANT OF SHARED FACILITIES RIGHTS 2.1 Grant by Northwest Ohio Wind; Vesting: 2.1.1 Grant by Northwest Ohio Wind. Northwest Ohio Wind hereby grants (i) to Northwest Ohio Solar, during the term of this Agreement, and on the terms and subject to the conditions hereof, the non-exclusive right to access and utilize the Shared Facilities as may be reasonably necessary in connection with Northwest Ohio Solar’s ownership, operation, and maintenance of the Northwest Ohio Solar Project; and (ii) to Interconnection Company during the term of this Agreement, and on the terms and subject to the conditions hereof, the non-exclusive right to access and utilize the Shared Facilities and the Northwest Ohio Wind Project, as may be reasonably necessary in connection with Interconnection Company’s obligations under this Agreement and under the ISA. 2.1.2 Vesting. The right to access and utilize the Shared Facilities granted to Northwest Ohio Solar hereunder shall vest in Northwest Ohio Solar as a contracting party hereunder without any transfer of title or leasehold interest in the Shared Facilities. 2.2 Grant by Co-Users; Vesting: 2.2.1 Grant by Co-Users. Co-Users hereby grant to Interconnection Company, during the term of this Agreement and subject to the conditions hereof, the non-exclusive right to access, control, and utilize the Project Facility as may be reasonably necessary in connection with Interconnection Company’s obligations under this Agreement and under the ISA. 2.2.2 Vesting. The right to access, control, and utilize the Project Facility granted to Interconnection Company hereunder shall vest in Interconnection Company as a contracting party hereunder without any transfer of title or leasehold interest in the Shared Facilities. 3. NATURE OF SHARED FACILITIES RIGHTS 3.1 Limitation on Grant: 3.1.1 Notwithstanding any other provision of this Agreement, the rights granted by Northwest Ohio Wind to Northwest Ohio Solar and by the Co-Users to Interconnection Company under this Agreement are granted only to the extent that such rights do not limit or interfere with the ability of Northwest Ohio Wind to (a) produce and deliver energy to the Point of Interconnection (as such term is defined in the ISA), (b) sell capacity, renewable energy credits, environmental attributes, ancillary services or similar or successor products or (c) perform its obligations under any agreement or contract it has entered into, or enters into after the date hereof, as the same may be hereafter modified or amended. For clarification by way of example, if PJM issues a curtailment order that limits but does not preclude power delivery into the electric grid from the Project Facility, then one hundred percent (100%) of the Northwest Ohio Solar Project will be curtailed prior to any curtailment of the Northwest Ohio Wind Project. 3.1.2 Co-Users shall take all actions to ensure the ability of Interconnection Company to comply with the requirements of PJM and AEP under the ISA or its successor with respect to the interconnection of the Project Facility. The Parties shall operate their respective Projects and the Shared Facilities in accordance with Prudent Industry Practices (as defined below) and in a manner that will not cause damage, loss, liability, penalties, fines, or costs to Northwest Ohio Wind, the Northwest Ohio Wind Project, or the Interconnection Company. 3.2 Authorization to Control Project Facility: 3.2.1 Control of Project Facility: The Co-Users grant to Interconnection Company, to the extent necessary, the right to (a) dispatch power as reasonably requested by Co-Users, or as directed or required by PJM or AEP under the ISA, (b) allow the Project Facility to participate in the PJM Capacity Market and (c) satisfy Co-Users’ obligations under energy purchase agreements, including the REPA. Such control and dispatch are subject to Section 3.1 and Section 3.2.5 and are dependent upon the availability of adequate interconnection capacity. 3.2.1.1 Interconnection Company shall operate the Project Facility as necessary to effectuate the dispatch or curtailment of energy, and shall be the sole Party which will interface with PJM on behalf of the Project Facility, including settlement and participation, if any, in the PJM markets. 3.2.1.2 For the avoidance of doubt, other than as may be required under the terms of the REPA, neither Co-User is agreeing to sell or satisfy any obligations of the other Co-User under (a) any agreement pursuant to which that Co-User is a party, (b) the REPA, or (c) with respect to any tariff pursuant to which that Co-User is subject, including any obligation on the part of that Co-User to sell capacity, energy, ancillary services, RECs, environmental attributes, or similar or successor products with respect to such Co-User’s Project. 3.2.2 Invoices and Payments: Co-Users grant to Interconnection Company the authority to send and receive invoices and payments to PJM on behalf of the Project Facility, pursuant to the ISA and Interconnection Company’s role as “Interconnection Customer” under and as defined in the ISA. 3.2.2.1 In the event that amounts are owed to PJM as a result of either Project, the Co User that owns such Project shall promptly remit such amounts to Interconnection Company (but in any event prior to the due date thereof) and Interconnection Company shall then promptly remit such payment amount to PJM. 3.2.2.2 In the event that Interconnection Company receives any amounts from PJM (or any other entity) on behalf of energy and/or capacity produced by either Project, Interconnection Company shall promptly remit such amounts to that Project’s Co-User; provided, however, that Interconnection Company may set-off from any payment owed to Northwest Ohio Solar any outstanding amounts due and payable by or on behalf of Northwest Ohio Solar to Northwest Ohio Wind pursuant to the terms hereof. 3.2.3 Meteorological and Operational Data: Co-Users shall make all meteorological and operational data available to Interconnection Company upon request. In addition, to the extent required to comply with Governmental Approvals or Laws, the Co-Users shall share meteorological and operational data regarding their respective Projects and the Shared Facilities with the Interconnection Company, with the mutual objective of optimizing the operational and maintenance efficiency of each of the Projects and the Shared Facilities. Other than as set forth in Section 10.1 hereof, the sharing Co-User makes no representation or warranty, express or implied, and will have no Liability with respect to any data provided under this Agreement, whether for completeness, accuracy or otherwise. The receiving Party will maintain the confidentiality of the data received in accordance with the requirements of this Agreement. 3.2.4 Metering and Settlement: Subject to Section 4, each Party agrees to cooperate with the other Parties to ensure that appropriate metering equipment, if necessary and required, is installed at each of the Projects and/or Shared Facilities to allow for individual measurement of the wind, solar, and storage portions of the Projects. As necessary, Interconnection Company shall communicate to PJM the metering information from both Projects, and facilitate settlement based on the metering data. The installation of any such metering equipment shall be at the cost and expense of the Co-User that owns the Project for which such equipment is being installed. 3.2.5 Penalties: No dispatch or sales of energy and/or capacity from Northwest Ohio Solar, and no participation in the PJM Market by or on behalf of Northwest Ohio Solar, shall be made if such dispatch or participation will result in the imposition of penalties on the Parties or constitute a violation of law, including the Federal Power Act. Without limiting any of Northwest Ohio Solar’s indemnification obligations in this Agreement or in any other agreement, if any such penalties are incurred as a result of dispatch, sales, or participation by or on behalf of Northwest Ohio Solar, the costs of such penalties shall be the responsibility of Northwest Ohio Solar. 3.2.6 Costs and Fees: All operational costs of Interconnection Company shall be paid by Northwest Ohio Wind. Northwest Ohio Solar shall pay to Northwest Ohio Wind a fixed annual fee of $7,800 for use of the Shared Facilities, and a fixed annual fee of $13,300 as contribution for Northwest Ohio Solar’s share of Interconnection Company’s and the Shared Facility’s operating expenses. 3.3 Assignment or Transfer: Northwest Ohio Solar and/or Interconnection Company shall not assign or transfer this Agreement (including an assignment or transfer in connection with a financing), or the rights granted hereunder or grant any permission, license, right of way or similar right to the rights granted hereunder without the prior written consent of Northwest Ohio Wind, which consent may be conditioned or withheld in Northwest Ohio Wind’s sole discretion. Any direct or indirect change in control of Northwest Ohio Solar or Interconnection Company that causes Northwest Ohio Solar or Interconnection Company to cease to be controlled by CMS Enterprises Company, a Michigan corporation (“CMS”), shall be deemed to be an assignment that requires Northwest Ohio Wind’s prior written consent. 3.4 Interference: In no event shall Northwest Ohio Solar be entitled to (a) modify the Shared Facilities or (b) exercise its rights to access and utilize the Shared Facilities if the exercise of such rights would materially interfere with or limit the reasonable and necessary access and utilization of the Shared Facilities by Northwest Ohio Wind. Each Party shall, to the fullest extent commercially reasonable and subject to Prudent Industry Practices and the other provisions of this Agreement, limit all interference with the use and enjoyment by the other Party, of its rights in and to the Shared Facilities. As used herein, “Prudent Industry Practices” means those practices, methods, equipment, specifications and standards of safety and performance, as the same may be changed from time to time, as are generally used in the operation and maintenance of privately owned wind generated electric power facilities (in the case of Northwest Ohio Wind) or solar generated electric power plus storage facilities (in the case of Northwest Ohio Solar) located in the same region as the Northwest Ohio Wind Project and of a comparable size to the Northwest Ohio Wind Project or the Northwest Ohio Solar Project, as applicable, which, at a particular time, in the exercise of reasonable judgment and in light of the facts known at the time the decision was made, are considered good, safe and prudent practice and would require a person to: (i) perform its duties in a commercially reasonable manner in compliance in all material respects with the requirements of all applicable laws (including environmental laws), insurance policies, all applicable licenses and permits, and applicable wind energy or solar energy, as applicable, industry standards, (ii) use sufficient and properly trained and skilled personnel, (iii) use parts and supplies that meet the specifications set forth in the applicable project documents and (iv) perform plant maintenance and replacement of parts in the normal course of operation taking into consideration warranty requirements and manufacturers’ recommendations. The Parties agree that the foregoing “Prudent Industry Practices” is not intended to be limited to the optimum practice, method or act to the exclusion of all others, but rather to be a spectrum of generally acceptable practices, methods or acts in light of the facts known at the applicable time. 4. COSTS AND MAINTENANCE OF SHARED FACILITIES 4.1 Ownership, Operation, and Maintenance of Shared Facilities: Northwest Ohio Wind, or Interconnection Company on behalf of and at the direction of Northwest Ohio Wind, shall have the exclusive right to undertake all operational, management, repair, and maintenance responsibilities with respect to the Shared Facilities consistent with Prudent Industry Practices and the terms of this Agreement. Such responsibilities shall include, but are not limited to, the right of Interconnection Company to curtail or disconnect, derate or dispatch down one or more of the Projects, in whole or in part, as necessary to respond to system emergencies, instructions from any Governmental Authority, including, but not limited to, PJM and AEP, maintenance needs, or any default under this Agreement. Northwest Ohio Wind shall have the right, but not the obligation, to direct operational, management, repair, and maintenance responsibilities with respect to the Shared Facilities. Northwest Ohio Solar acknowledges and agrees that Northwest Ohio Wind and/or Interconnection Company shall not be responsible to indemnify or make Northwest Ohio Solar whole in the event that Northwest Ohio Solar fails to receive revenue payments (including energy, green attributes, capacity, or other products) under any power purchase agreement, tariff or through PJM market participation as a result of as a result of Northwest Ohio Wind’s and/or Interconnection Company’s operation, management, repair, and maintenance activities and omissions under this Agreement. The Parties shall work cooperatively to meet the operational, maintenance, and cyber security requirements issued by NERC, as implemented by ReliabilityFirst Corporation. 4.2 Allocation of Certain Costs and Expenses: As between the Co-Users, each such Party shall be responsible for all costs of use, possession, operation, inspection, maintenance, repair, alteration, modification, relocation, improvement, repairs and replacement of the Shared Facilities to the extent the foregoing benefit solely such Party’s own Project. Operation and maintenance expenses (including costs of obtaining and maintaining insurance, and costs of obtaining and maintaining permits and approvals (other than to the extent otherwise expressly set forth in this Agreement)) and any budgeted capital expenditures or major maintenance expenses in each case with respect to the Shared Facilities that benefit both Projects shall be allocated between Northwest Ohio Wind and Northwest Ohio Solar based on each Party’s proportionate share of the aggregate nameplate capacity of the Project Facility. 4.3 Regulatory Approvals: Northwest Ohio Solar shall be responsible for all costs and expenses associated with securing any approval of this Agreement or the transactions contemplated thereby from the FERC, PJM, or any other Governmental Authority. 4.4 Successor Agreement: Without limiting Section 3.3, in the event that the Northwest Ohio Wind Project and the Northwest Ohio Solar Project are no longer operated and maintained by and under the control of CMS for any reason, the Parties agree to use good faith efforts to negotiate mutually agreeable terms and execute a mutually agreeable agreement (or amendment to this Agreement) that specifies the division of responsibilities of the Parties providing operation and maintenance services associated with the Shared Facilities for each Project. 5. CHANGE IN LAW 5.1 Change in Law: In the event that a change in the laws or regulations applicable to the Project Facility or this Agreement requires the amendment, modification or replacement of this Agreement in order to satisfy any applicable federal, state or local regulatory requirements, the Parties agree to use good faith efforts (at the sole cost and expense of Northwest Ohio Solar) to negotiate and implement mutually agreeable terms to accomplish such amendment, modification or replacement; provided, however, that if such amendment, modification or replacement is required because of a change in law or regulation that is applicable to the Northwest Ohio Wind Project only, then such amendment, modification or replacement shall be at the sole cost and expense of Northwest Ohio Wind. 6. FORCE MAJEURE 6.1 Force Majeure: In the event of an act of God, government order or restraint, war (declared or undeclared) or warlike conditions, act of terrorism, blockade, revolution, strike, lockout, civil commotion, fire, flood, storm, epidemic or any other occurrence beyond a Party’s reasonable control (each a “Force Majeure Event”), such Party shall promptly notify the other Party thereof and, so long as such condition shall persist, such Party shall not be liable for the delay in performance of, or the failure to perform, its obligations (other than obligations for payment of amounts due hereunder) under this Agreement caused directly or indirectly thereby. The claiming Party shall give the other Parties notice describing the particulars of the Force Majeure Event. Within fifteen (15) days after giving notice of the Force Majeure Event, the claiming Party shall give the other Parties an estimate of the Force Majeure Event’s expected duration and probable impact. The claiming Party shall continue to furnish the other Parties with timely regular reports during the continuation of the Force Majeure Event. Each Party shall immediately exercise commercially reasonable efforts to mitigate or limit the impact to its obligations hereunder as a result of the Force Majeure Event. 7. PAYMENTS 7.1 Billing. Billing and payment of the any amounts due and payable under this Agreement shall be as follows: 7.1.1 If one Party believes any other Party owes amounts to it hereunder, such Party shall issue an invoice to the other Parties and shall provide the supporting data to support its claim for payment. 7.1.2 Invoices shall be sent to the address set forth in Exhibit B. 7.1.3 If a Party receives an invoice from another Party, it shall pay the undisputed amounts set forth in such invoice by wire transfer of immediately available funds to the account designated by such other Party on or before the date that is fifteen (15) days after its receipt of such invoice (the “Payment Date”). Any amounts that are not paid by the Payment Date shall thereafter accrue interest on the aggregate, outstanding balance of such amounts from the Payment Date to and including the date such payment is made at a per annum rate equal to the lesser of (i) a per annum rate equal to the rate of interest published in The Wall Street Journal as the prime lending rate or “prime rate”, with adjustments in that varying rate to be made on the same date as any change in that rate is so published, plus three percent (3%) or (ii) the highest per annum rate of interest that may be charged in accordance with applicable law (such per annum rate, the “Interest Rate”). 7.2 Disputed Invoices. The Party disputing an invoice shall notify the other Parties that it disputes such invoice prior to the due date for payment as set forth in Section 7.1.3 and, within forty-five (45) days of the issuance of the disputed invoice, such disputing Party shall provide the other Parties a detailed writing explaining the basis for the dispute. The Parties shall, within fifteen (15) days of the non-disputing Party’s receipt of the Party’s explanation for the basis of such dispute, hold a meeting attended by senior officers of each Party and use commercially reasonable efforts to amicably and promptly resolve the dispute. If, within fifteen (15) days after such meeting of the Parties have not resolved the dispute, the Parties may exercise any other remedy available at law or in equity to resolve the dispute. Upon resolution of any dispute, if all or part of the disputed amount is later determined to have been due or paid but not due, then the Party owing such payment or refund shall pay the other Parties within fifteen (15) days after receipt of notice of such determination the amount determined to be due plus interest thereon at the Interest Rate from the date due or overpaid to and including the date of payment or refund, as applicable. If a Party fails to dispute an invoice within twelve (12) months from its issuance, such Party shall be precluded from later disputing such invoice. 8. DEFAULT AND REMEDIES 8.1 Events of Default. The occurrence of any of the following shall constitute a default by Northwest Ohio Solar under this Agreement (each, an “Event of Default”): 8.1.1 the failure by Northwest Ohio Solar to pay in full any amount payable by it hereunder when due, where such failure is not cured within ten (10) Business Days after written notice by Northwest Ohio Wind of such failure; 8.1.2 the levy, seizure, assignment or sale of a substantial part of Northwest Ohio Solar’s property for or by any creditor or Governmental Authority; 8.1.3 the failure by Northwest Ohio Solar to maintain performance assurance as required pursuant to Section 11.5; 8.1.4 in the event that the performance assurance maintained by Northwest Ohio Solar is in the form of a guaranty, the applicable guarantor repudiates, denies, disavows or breaches any of its obligations under such guaranty (after giving effect to any applicable cure or grace period under such guaranty); 8.1.5 a breach of a representation or warranty provided by Northwest Ohio Solar herein which has, or could reasonably be expected to have, a material adverse effect on the rights of Northwest Ohio Wind or Interconnection Company under this Agreement or otherwise and such breach is not cured within thirty (30) days after written notice thereof from Northwest Ohio Wind or Interconnection Company; provided, however, that if such breach cannot reasonably be cured within the thirty (30) day period, and Northwest Ohio Solar has commenced and is diligently pursuing such cure, the cure period shall be extended to not more than sixty (60) days after the written notice of default as shall be necessary for Northwest Ohio Solar to promptly cure such breach; 8.1.6 a breach by Northwest Ohio Solar in observing or performing any of its obligations set forth in this Agreement, other than those described in clauses 8.1.1.1 through 8.1.1.3 above, which breach has, or could reasonably be expected to have a material adverse effect on the rights of Northwest Ohio Wind or Interconnection Company under this Agreement or otherwise and such breach is not cured within thirty (30) days after written notice thereof from Northwest Ohio Wind or Interconnection Company; provided, however, that if such breach cannot reasonably be cured within the thirty (30) day period, and if Northwest Ohio Solar has commenced and is diligently pursuing such cure, the cure period shall be extended to not more than ninety (90) days after the written notice of default, as shall be necessary for Northwest Ohio Solar to promptly cure such breach; provided, further, however, that no cure period shall apply to a breach by Northwest Ohio Solar of Section 9.2; 8.1.7 Northwest Ohio Solar commences any case, proceeding or other action seeking reorganization, arrangement, adjustment, liquidation, dissolution or composition of itself or its debts or assets, or adopts an arrangement with or makes an assignment for the benefit of creditors, under any bankruptcy, moratorium, rearrangement, insolvency, reorganization or similar law for the relief of creditors or affecting the rights or remedies of creditors in general or is declared insolvent or Northwest Ohio Solar conceals or removes any part of its property with the intent to hinder, delay or defraud its creditors, or makes or suffers any transfer of its property which may be fraudulent under applicable law, or admits in writing its inability to pay its debts; or 8.1.8 there shall be instituted against Northwest Ohio Solar any case, proceeding or action seeking reorganization, arrangement, adjustment, liquidation, dissolution or composition of Northwest Ohio Solar or its debts or assets, which case, proceeding or action shall not have been terminated, stayed or dismissed within sixty (60) days after commencement, or a trustee, receiver, custodian or other like official is appointed for or to take possession of all or any part of the property or assets of Northwest Ohio Solar. 8.2 Remedies. If an Event of Default has occurred and is continuing, Northwest Ohio Wind and Interconnection Company shall have the following rights and remedies: 8.2.1 To receive amounts payable under the indemnities contained herein; 8.2.2 To exercise any and all other rights and remedies that Northwest Ohio Wind or Interconnection Company might otherwise have at law or in equity (subject to any limitations set forth herein with respect to the same); and 8.2.3 Terminate this Agreement, which termination shall become effective ten (10) days after Northwest Ohio Wind provides notice of such termination to Northwest Ohio Solar, subject to obtaining any prior authorizations and approvals required with respect to such termination by FERC or any other Governmental Authority pursuant to applicable law. 9. REPRESENTATIONS AND WARRANTIES; COVENANTS 9.1 Representations and Warranties. As of the Effective Date, Northwest Ohio Solar represents and warrants for the benefit of Northwest Ohio Wind: 9.1.1 it is an entity duly organized, validly existing and in good standing under the laws of its jurisdiction of formation and is duly qualified or licensed to do business in all jurisdictions where it is required to be so qualified or licensed; 9.1.2 it has the necessary limited liability power and authority to enter into and perform its obligations under this Agreement; 9.1.3 it is in compliance in all material respects with all applicable laws relating to the ownership, operation and sale of energy or other products produced from the Northwest Ohio Solar Project; 9.1.4 it has duly authorized the person(s) signing this Agreement to execute this Agreement on its behalf; 9.1.5 upon execution, this Agreement will be a legal, valid and binding obligation of such Party, enforceable against such Party in accordance with its terms; 9.1.6 the execution and delivery of this Agreement and the performance by Northwest Ohio Solar hereunder will not violate, result in a breach of or conflict in any material respect with any law, rule, regulation, order or decree applicable to Northwest Ohio Solar, its organizational documents or the terms of any other material agreement binding on Northwest Ohio Solar; 9.1.7 no suit, action or arbitration, or legal, administrative or other proceeding is pending or, to its knowledge, threatened (in writing) against it that would affect the validity or enforceability of this Agreement against Northwest Ohio Solar or its ability to perform its obligations hereunder; and 9.1.8 it has not, directly or indirectly, created, incurred or permitted to exist, any Lien on the right, title and interest of Northwest Ohio Wind in the Shared Facilities. 9.2 Covenants. Northwest Ohio Solar covenants that it will not operate the Northwest Ohio Solar Project until Northwest Ohio Wind provides it with written notice stating that the Condition Precedent set forth in Section 1.2 of this Agreement has been satisfied in Northwest Ohio Wind’s sole discretion. 10. INDEMNITY 10.1 Northwest Ohio Solar shall indemnify Northwest Ohio Wind and Interconnection Company for any Claims asserted against, imposed upon, or incurred by Northwest Ohio Wind or Interconnection Company related to any and all events or occurrences at the Northwest Ohio Solar Project site or relating to the Northwest Ohio Solar Project (in either case, regardless of whether such event or occurrence is an event of force majeure, an intentional or unintentional event, or a planned or unplanned event) or any action or inaction on the part of Northwest Ohio Solar or any person acting for or on its behalf, including Northwest Ohio Wind and Interconnection Company, or any of its contractors, consultants or representatives (regardless of whether Northwest Ohio Solar or such other persons acted in good faith or in accordance with Prudent Industry Practice), whether past, present or future, including without limitation (i) any energy transactions between Northwest Ohio Solar and Northwest Ohio Wind and/or Interconnection Company, (ii) any violations of applicable law relating to the operation or ownership of the Northwest Ohio Solar Project, (iii) any breach of Northwest Ohio Wind’s and/or Interconnection Company’s agreements with third parties caused by the operation or ownership of the Northwest Ohio Solar Project or the sale of electricity therefrom, (iv) any other commercial relationship between Northwest Ohio Wind and/or Interconnection Company and Northwest Ohio Solar, including any failure on the part of either Party to make any filings with, requests of, or disclosures to any Governmental Authority related to the activities of Northwest Ohio Solar or the Northwest Ohio Solar Project, (v) any inaccurate or faulty meteorological and operational data provided by or on behalf of Northwest Ohio Solar or the Northwest Ohio Solar Project to the other Parties hereto, (vi) any obligations on the part of Northwest Ohio Wind or Interconnection Company under or as a result of the ISA that are related to, or caused by, the Northwest Ohio Solar Project regardless of whether Northwest Ohio Wind or the Interconnection Company have agreed to be primarily responsible for such obligations pursuant to the terms of the ISA (including any assignment thereof), (vii) any performance by the Interconnection Company under the ISA and/or this Agreement in advance of a FERC order accepting or approving the ISA Assignment without modification or (viii) any development, construction or financing activities related to the Northwest Ohio Solar Project, including any such development, construction or financing activities performed by Northwest Ohio Wind and/or Interconnection Company (any such Claim, an “Indemnifiable Claim”). For the avoidance of any doubt, Indemnifiable Claims shall include claims between the Parties and claims made by Third Parties and recovery for Indemnifiable Claims shall include, without limitation, the cost of replacing or repairing all or any of the equipment or components of the Northwest Ohio Wind Project, the Shared Facilities, and the amount of any lost revenue and tax benefits for the Northwest Ohio Wind Project as a result of any downtime or curtailment caused by such Indemnifiable Claim. 10.2 As used in this Section 10, the term “Claims” means all claims, suits, demands, injunctions, actions, causes of action, assessments, cleanup and remedial obligations, judgments, awards, liabilities, losses (including amounts paid in settlement of claims), damages, fines, fees, taxes, penalties, costs and expenses of every kind and character (including litigation costs and reasonable attorneys’ and experts’ fees and expenses, including such fees and expenses at trial and on any appeal and any proceeding to enforce indemnification rights under Section 10.1). 10.3 If an Indemnifiable Claim is under dispute and such Indemnifiable Claim relates to a matter within the expertise of an independent engineer, then the Parties shall endeavor to consult with a nationally recognized independent engineer reasonably satisfactory to both Parties in the field of wind and solar energy generation projects (the “Independent Engineer”) to resolve such dispute and opine on the amount of the Indemnifiable Claim, if any. Subject to any confidentiality undertakings and without limiting the scope of any applicable attorney-client privilege and without requiring any disclosure of proprietary information, the Parties agree that they shall submit any pertinent information, applicable books and records, and all other data, in each case reasonably requested by the Independent Engineer and necessary for the Independent Engineer to make its determination. The determination of the Independent Engineer in resolving a dispute pursuant to this Section 10.3 shall be final and binding upon the Parties. Northwest Ohio Solar shall be responsible for the payment of the fees, costs and expenses of the Independent Engineer. 10.4 Aggregate Limitation of Liability for Northwest Ohio Wind Project. Notwithstanding any other provision of this Agreement to the contrary, the liability of Northwest Ohio Wind and/or Interconnection Company arising out of or relating to this Agreement in any calendar year from any and all causes, whether based in contract, strict liability, tort (including negligence), or any other cause of action shall in no event exceed an amount equal to the aggregate amount payable to Northwest Ohio Wind pursuant to this Agreement for the then-current calendar year and the prior calendar year. 10.5 Subject to the other provisions of this Agreement relating to Indemnifiable Claims, if no remedy for Claims is expressly provided herein, the indemnification obligations of a Party hereunder shall be limited to actual damages and shall not include special, incidental, consequential, indirect, punitive, or exemplary damages; provided, that any special, incidental, consequential, indirect, punitive, or exemplary damages recovered by a third party (including Governmental Authorities) against a Party entitled to indemnity pursuant hereto shall be included in the damages recoverable under such indemnity; and provided, further, that the loss, disallowance or reduction of PTCs or other tax benefits shall not be considered as special, incidental, consequential, indirect, punitive or exemplary damages. For the avoidance of doubt, this Section 10.5 does not limit in any way third-party Claims that are subject to indemnification pursuant to Section 10.1. 11. MISCELLANEOUS 11.1 Agreement to Cooperate. Each Party agrees to reasonably cooperate with the other Parties so that, subject to the terms of this Agreement, each Project benefits from the full utilization and enjoyment of the Shared Facilities as is necessary for the efficient operation of the Northwest Ohio Wind Project and the Northwest Ohio Solar Project, respectively. 11.2 Relationship of Parties. The Parties do not intend to create hereby any joint venture, partnership, association or any other entity for the conduct of any business and, other than as expressly set forth herein with respect to the obligations of Interconnection Company, nothing herein shall be deemed to authorize either Party to act on behalf of the other Party. 11.3 Modification and Amendment. The terms of this Agreement may only be modified or amended in a writing signed by all of the Parties and shall be subject to acceptance or approval by FERC. 11.4 Waiver. The failure of a Party to insist upon or enforce strict performance of any of the provisions of this Agreement or to exercise any rights or remedies under this Agreement shall not be construed as a waiver or relinquishment to any extent of such Party’s right to assert or rely upon any such provisions, rights and remedies in that or any other instance; rather, the same shall be and remain in full force and effect. 11.5 Performance Assurance. On the Execution Date, Northwest Ohio Solar shall provide Northwest Ohio Wind and Interconnection Company a copy of that certain Guaranty duly executed and delivered by CMS Enterprises Company, a Michigan corporation (the “Sponsor Guarantor”), in favor of Northwest Ohio Wind, Interconnection Company and Wells Fargo Central Pacific Holdings, Inc., in form and substance reasonably satisfactory to Northwest Ohio Wind, to secure Northwest Ohio Solar’s performance of its obligations hereunder. Such guaranty shall remain in full force and effect until performance in full of Northwest Ohio Solar’s obligations in connection with this Agreement. 11.6 Enforceability. Any provision of this Agreement which is prohibited or unenforceable in any jurisdiction shall, as to such jurisdiction, be ineffective only to the extent of such prohibition, but shall be effective to the extent of such remaining provisions hereof. 11.7 Liens. Neither Northwest Ohio Solar nor Interconnection Company shall, after the Effective Date, directly or indirectly, create, incur or permit to exist, any Lien on the right, title and interest of Northwest Ohio Wind in the Shared Facilities. If any such Lien exists or arises after the Effective Date, Northwest Ohio Solar shall cause such Lien to be released and removed of record within thirty (30) days after becoming aware of the existence thereof. “Lien” means encumbrances, liens, charges, pledges, collateral assignments, options, mortgages, warrants, deeds of trust, security interests, claims, assessments, easements, variances, purchase rights, rights of first refusal, reservations, encroachments, irregularities, deficiencies, defaults, defects, adverse claims, interests, and other matters of every type and description whatsoever, whether voluntary or involuntary, choate or inchoate or imposed by law, agreement (including any agreement to give any of the foregoing or any conditional sale or other title retention agreement), understanding, or otherwise, and whether or not of record, impairing or affecting the title to real or personal property; provided, however, that notwithstanding anything to the contrary herein, in no event shall “Lien” include or be deemed to include: (A) liens imposed by any Governmental Authority for taxes that are not yet due and payable or for taxes being contested in good faith by appropriate proceedings so long as such proceedings do not involve a material risk of the sale, forfeiture, loss or restriction on the use of the Shared Facilities; (B) liens on the Shared Facilities arising out of judgments or awards so long as an appeal or proceeding for review is being prosecuted in good faith and for the payment of which adequate reserves, bonds or other security have been provided or are fully covered by insurance; (C) liens held by Northwest Ohio Wind on the Shared Facilities; and (D) liens on the Shared Facilities that were granted to third parties by Northwest Ohio Wind or that arise in connection with obligations of Northwest Ohio Wind. 11.8 Governing Law. This Agreement shall be governed by and interpreted in accordance with the laws of the State of Ohio. Venue shall be proper in an Ohio state or federal court having jurisdiction over the county where the Property is located. The Parties agree that any rule of construction to the effect that ambiguities are to be resolved in favor of either Party shall not be employed in the interpretation of this Agreement and is waived. 11.9 Inspection of Records. Each Party shall have access to any records concerning the Shared Facilities held by the other Party upon reasonable notice and at reasonable times. 11.10 Notices. All notices, requests, demands, declarations and other communications required hereunder or given pursuant hereto shall be in writing and shall become effective (i) if given by registered or certified mail, three business days after being deposited with the U.S. Postal Service, postage prepaid, or, if earlier, upon receipt, (ii) if given by courier, when delivered by such courier or (iii) if personally delivered, when so delivered in person, in each case to the address set forth on Exhibit B for the applicable Party. 11.11 Section Headings. The section headings in this Agreement are for convenience of reference only and shall not modify, define, expand, or limit any of the terms or provisions hereof. 11.12 Counterparts. This Agreement may be executed in one or more counterparts, each of which when so executed shall be deemed an original, and all of which when taken together shall constitute one and the same instrument.
